query.result:
1 The concubine of ancient Tithonus 2 already was whitening on the balcony of the east, 3 outside of the arms of her sweet companion;
4 with gems her forehead was shining, 5 placed in the figure of the cold animal 6 that with the tail strikes the people;
7 and the night, with the steps with which it rises, 8 had made two in the place where we were, 9 and the third already was bending downwards its wings;
10 when I, who with me had of that of Adam, 11 overcome by sleep, on the grass I bent 12 there where already all five of us were sitting.

31 There it seemed that she and I were burning;
32 and so the imagined fire blazed,
33 that it was necessary that the sleep be broken.

34 Not otherwise Achilles awoke, 35 the eyes awakened turning around 36 and not knowing where he was,
37 when the mother from Chiron to Scyro 38 carried him away sleeping in her arms, 39 whence afterwards the Greeks departed him;
40 that I shook myself, just as from the face 41 fled from me the sleep, and became numb, 42 as does the man who, frightened, freezes.

